Three days later, on 11 August 1937, Iezhov issued Operative Order No. 00485, which is regarded as the beginning of the Polish Operation. He ordered the initiation of a massive operation to ‘completely annihilate the local organizations of the PMO, especially the sabotaging, spying and rebellious cadres,’ starting on 20 August 1937. The operation was to end within three months. Subjected to arrest were following groups:

a) activists of the PMO, who have already been detected, but not found yet;

b) all POWs from the Polish Army, who had remained in the Soviet Union;

c) all refugees from Poland;

d) political emigrants from Poland and persons who came to the USSR through prisoner exchanges;

e) former members of the Polish Socialist Party and other anti-Soviet parties;

f) the most active part of the local anti-Soviet, nationalistic elements in the Polish national districts.57
